\begin_layout Section
Equation of motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:TISE"

\end_inset

 Throughout this work, we are going to require an accurate description of our system to simulate various processes. In order to achieve this, we must consider systems at the microscopic scale that obey Quantum Mechanics. Therefore, the wavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ket{\psi_n(\mathbf{r},t)}$
\end_inset

 represents the eigenstates and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the total energy operator for a given problem, that satisfies the Schrödinger equation, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:TDSE}
	H\Ket{\psi_n(\mathbf{r},t)}=i\hbar\frac{\partial\Ket{\psi_n(\mathbf{r},t)}}{\partial t},
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 denotes the ensemble of spatial co-ordinates. We shall leave the Hamiltonian operator undefined as we will discuss this in greater detail during Section (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:theham"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aim of this project is to obtain stationary states, where the system isindependent with respect to the time component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_n(\mathbf{r},t)$
\end_inset

, i.e. the state is unchanged for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_n(\mathbf{r},t) =\psi_n(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

. Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TDSE"

\end_inset

) is simple to solve for the hydrogen atom or hydrogenic ions, but becomes complicated when expanding to include many electrons. Generally the time dependency can be dropped as we obtain identical results when considering a wavepacket with evolution time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

. We then make the assumption of separation of variables to solve (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TDSE"

\end_inset

) by rewriting, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:SOV}
	\Ket{\psi_n(\mathbf{r},t)}=\Ket{\psi_n(\mathbf{r})\phi_n(t)}.
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

Upon direct substitution of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SOV"

\end_inset

) into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TDSE"

\end_inset

) and selecting the separation constant as 
\begin_inset Formula $E_n$
\end_inset

, it can be shown that if the 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 has a time independent potential energy operator 
\begin_inset Formula $V(r)$
\end_inset

, then it is possible to determine stationary states of the problem, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:TDwave}
	\Ket{\psi_n(\mathbf{r},t)}=e^{-iE_nt/\hbar}\Ket{\psi_n(\mathbf{r})}.
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

We can then arrive at the desired result, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:TISE}
	H\Ket{\psi_n(\mathbf{r})}=E_n\Ket{\psi_n(\mathbf{r})}.
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

This is known as the time-independent Schrödinger equation. This eigenvalue equation has eigenvector solutions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ket{\psi_n(\mathbf{r})}$
\end_inset

 with corresponding eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $E_n$
\end_inset

 for each state with index 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution of this equation is simple for one-electron systems and analytical solutions do exist and are readily obtainable. The solution can be determined by a separation of variables into a set of radial (r), and spherical (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta, \phi$
\end_inset

) coordinates, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:fullwave}
	\Ket{\psi_{nlm_l}(\mathbf{r})}=\Ket{R(r)\Theta(\theta)\Phi(\phi)}=\Ket{R_{nl}(r)Y_{lm_l}(\theta,\phi)}.
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

The wavefunction depends on a set of quantum numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_l$
\end_inset

, which will become clearer in the following sections when we look at a particular energy operator 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

. We combine the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 components to construct the well known Spherical Harmonics, Y
\begin_inset Formula $_{lm_l}$
\end_inset

 as these functions are easily calculated. They are simply Legendre polynomial expansions of cosine functions as their argument and therefore reduces the problem to solving for the radial component of the wavefunction, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{nl}(r)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:theham"

\end_inset

 The Hamiltonian is a representation of the total energy for some system which can be constructed from its kinetic and potential energy, written below as, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:TV1V2}
	H=T+V_i=T(\mathbf{r})+V_1(\mathbf{r}) + V_2(\mathbf{r})
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the kinetic energy operator and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_2$
\end_inset

 are two potential energy operators. Once we define appropriate forms for the kinetic and potential energy, we are then in a position to determine the Radial contribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{nl}(r)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can think of a simplistic model for an atomic system containing a few negatively charged electrons surrounding a positive nucleus. This is advantageous in understanding the concepts that are implemented for construction of larger, multi-electron systems. We must therefore consider the effects of three forces, namely the kinetic energy of the electrons, the Coulomb interaction between each orbiting electron and positive nucleus and finally, the repulsive force that the other electrons feel from one another. Obviously the electron-electron repulsion charge can be neglected completely, for one-electron systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to proceed, we assume that the nucleus is infinitely heavy (a point mass) comparable to the mass of the remaining electrons present. To generalize further, we consider the system with a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-electrons and nuclear charge denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

. The kinetic energy operator can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:T}
	T=\sum_{i=1}^N-\frac{1}{2}\nabla_i^2,
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

for each of the electrons 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and therefore we sum over all 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 electrons. The Laplacian operator is also written in spherical polar coordinates to maintain consistency. Next we consider the interaction of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 electron with the infinitely heavy nucleus. This potential scales as one over the radial separation between the two particles 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:V1}
	V_1=\sum_{i=1}^N-\frac{Z}{r_i},
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_i$
\end_inset

 is the electron radius from the nucleus and the summation is over all the electrons again. And finally, the second Coulomb interaction which is that between each electron is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:V2}
	V_2=\sum_{i<j}^N\frac{1}{\mathbf{r}_{ij}},
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{ij} = | \mathbf{r}_i - \mathbf{r}_j | $
\end_inset

. In total, the Hamiltonian is therefore the sum of the three equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:T"

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:V1"

\end_inset

), and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:V2"

\end_inset

) and then by substituting into equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TV1V2"

\end_inset

) to obtain, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:ham}
	H=\sum_{i=1}^N-\frac{1}{2}\nabla_i^2-\frac{Z}{r_i}+\sum_{i<j}^N\frac{1}{\mathbf{r}_{ij}}.
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

Upon substitution of this into equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TISE"

\end_inset

) and assuming separation of variables, we can finally solve this basic one electron problem, through means of trivial analytical methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The radial and angular parts of equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TISE"

\end_inset

) are then separable by a constant we define here by 
\begin_inset Formula $l(l+1)$
\end_inset

. By rewriting the orbital angular momentum operators in terms of spherical co-ordinates, we can obtain the following eigenvalue equations, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
	\mathbf{L}^2Y_{lm_l}(\theta,\psi)=l(l+1)Y_{lm_l}(\theta,\psi)
	\]
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
	\mathbf{L}_zY_{lm_l}(\theta,\psi)=m_lY_{lm_l}(\theta,\psi)
	\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{L}^2$
\end_inset

 is the total angular momentum operator squared and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{L}_z$
\end_inset

 is it's 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-component, both represented in spherical polar coordinates. This is where we first introduce the orbital angular momentum quantum number 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and magnetic quantum number 
\begin_inset Formula $m_l$
\end_inset

, which has an explicit dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $-l \le m_l \le +l$
\end_inset

. From this, it is then possible to obtain the wavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\mathbf{r},\theta,\phi)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the radial functions and spherical harmonics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The form of equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ham"

\end_inset

) is usually an adequate description, but as 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 increases, we must account for relativistic effects. This is due to the fact that the inner most electrons feel a much stronger attractive force from the nucleus. Therefore, assuming the importance of relativistic effects, we must look at the Dirac equation and solve it to obtain the Breit-Pauli Hamiltonian. We can now separate the relativistic and non-relativisitc contributions of the Hamiltonian in the following way, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:hbp}
	H_{\text{BP}}=H_{\text{NR}}+H_{\text{REL}}.
	\end{equation}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{NR}}$
\end_inset

 is simply that of equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ham"

\end_inset

), and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{REL}}$
\end_inset

 is defined by one and two body correction terms, which leads to further splittings of the energy levels. In order to keep the calculations to be discussed in Chapter (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:rmatrix"

\end_inset

) manageable, we will only be concerned with the one-body terms which are defined by, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:bp1}
	H_{\text{mc}}=-\frac{1}{8}\alpha^2\sum_{i=1}^N\nabla_i^4,
	\end{equation}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:bp2}
	H_{\text{D}}=-\frac{1}{8}\alpha^2Z\sum_{i=1}^N\nabla_i^2\frac{1}{r_i},
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:bp3}
	H_{\text{SO}}=\frac{1}{2}\alpha^2\sum_{i=1}^N\frac{\mathbf{l}_i.\mathbf{s}_i}{r_i^3}.
	\end{equation}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{mc}}$
\end_inset

 is the mass correction term, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{D}}$
\end_inset

 is the Darwin term and finally 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{SO}}$
\end_inset

 is the spin-orbit term which deals with the coupling between the spin and orbital angular momentum of all each electron. 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the fine structure constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{l}_i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_i$
\end_inset

 are the spin and orbital angular momentum of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{\text{th}}$
\end_inset

 electron. The two body terms can of course be included as an extension to equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hbp"

\end_inset

), but the corrections are generally not significant enough for our purpose. The disadvantage of using equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hbp"

\end_inset

) over the non-relativistic approach is that it does not commute with the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{L}^2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{L}_z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}^2$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}_z$
\end_inset

 due to the additional coupling correction in equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bp3"

\end_inset

). Informally, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are referred to as `bad' quantum numbers and we are forced to introduce a new operator that will commute with 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{REL}$
\end_inset

. The relativistic form of the operator is just the addition of equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bp1"

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bp2"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bp3"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:hrel}
	H_{REL}=H_{mc}+H_D+H_{SO}.
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

An accurate description of the system is clearly essential, and equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hrel"

\end_inset

) provides a useful energy operator. For more complex systems, we must obtain approximate wavefunction expansions by applying numerical techniques. The following sections discuss various approaches with the Hamiltonian operators defined so far.
\end_layout

