\begin_layout Standard
In order to overcome this problem with Hartree's initial wavefunction in equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hartreeswf"

\end_inset

), Fock and Slater proposed a remedy by rewriting 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 in terms of an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 dimensional Slater determinant, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:slaterdet}
	\psi(q_1,..,q_N) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{N!}}\left| \begin{array}{cccc}
	u_{\alpha_1}(q_1) & u_{\alpha_2}(q_1) & ... & u_{\alpha_\nu}(q_1)\\
	u_{\alpha_1}(q_2) & u_{\alpha_2}(q_2) & ... & u_{\alpha_\nu}(q_2)\\
	\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
	u_{\alpha_1}(q_N) & u_{\alpha_2}(q_N) & ... & u_{\alpha_\nu}(q_N) \end{array} \right|.
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

Each 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_1, \alpha_2, ... , \alpha_\nu$
\end_inset

 denote a set of 4 quantum numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{n, l, m_l, m_s\}$
\end_inset

 in accordance with the Pauli exclusion principle. The factor in front of the determinant is to ensure the wavefunction is to be normalized to unity. It is also required that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\alpha_{\lambda}}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 in equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:slaterdet"

\end_inset

) are orthonormal to one another such that, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
	\Braket{u_\lambda | u_\mu} = \int u_\lambda^*(q)u_\mu(q)dq = \delta_{\lambda\mu}
	\]
\end_inset

where the integral is over all spatial co-ordinates and, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
	\Braket{\chi | \chi} = \sum_{m_s=-1/2}^{m_s =+1/2}  = \delta.
	\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ground state of atomic Ne has the electronic configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $1s^22s^22p^6$
\end_inset

, each subshell being completely full. There are 10 unique possibilities for the quantum numbers to be distributed (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=10$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The antisymmetric properties arise from the interchange of two rows or two columns, which results in the change of sign of the wavefunction. Another violation occurs when a set of quantum numbers are equal to each other (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_i=\alpha_j$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can attempt to obtain an optimal Slater Determinant by consideration of the non-relativistic Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{NR}}$
\end_inset

, from equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ham"

\end_inset

). In the central field approximation, it was possible to alter the Hamiltonian in such a way to apply perturbation theory. Another approximate method that can be applied whenever it is difficult to find a good description of an unperturbed Hamiltonian is the variational principle. We assume some trial wavefunction with adjustable (variational) parameters and we optimize these parameters until the wavefunction is minimized. The approximate energy functional corresponding some trial wavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is given by, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{varmethod}
	E_0\leq E[\Phi]= \frac{\Braket{\Phi |H|\Phi}}{\Braket{\Phi |\Phi}}
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

which provides an upper bound to the ground state energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_0$
\end_inset

. The reason for applying this Variational method is to deduce the unknown radial functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{nl}(r)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minimisation is subject to the orthonormality constraints. The functional 
\begin_inset Formula $E[\psi]$
\end_inset

 in equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "varmethod"

\end_inset

), is then stationary with respect to small variations of the orbitals 
\begin_inset Formula $u_\lambda$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\alpha_1, \alpha_2,..., \alpha_\nu$
\end_inset

. By applying a small change to equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "varmethod"

\end_inset

) we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula \[
	\delta E-\sum^N_{\lambda = \alpha_1}\sum^N_{\mu = \alpha_1}\mathcal{L}_{\lambda\mu}\delta\Braket{u_\mu |u_\lambda}=0,
	\]
\end_inset

where we have introduced 
\begin_inset Formula $N^2$
\end_inset

 Lagrange multipliers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\lambda\mu}$
\end_inset

. It is possible to obtain a new diagonal matrix of Lagrange multipliers by performing a unitary transformation on the spin orbitals, 
\begin_inset Formula $U\mathcal{L} = \mathcal{L}??$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\lambda\mu} = \mathcal{L}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

. A new set of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 integro-differential equations can be obtained, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
	\Big[-\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{r}_i}^2+\mathcal{V}(q_i)\Big]u_\lambda(q_i)=E_\lambda u_\lambda(q_i)
	\end{equation}
\end_inset

which take the similar form of equation (..) and where the new potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}(q_i)$
\end_inset

 is defined as, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
	\mathcal{V}(q_i)=-\frac{Z}{r_i}+\sum_{\mu}\int u_\lambda^*(\mathbf{r}_j)\frac{1}{r_{ij}}u_\lambda(\mathbf{r}_j)d\mathbf{r}_j-\sum_\lambda ...
	\]
\end_inset

We note here that we have expressed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}(q_i)$
\end_inset

