\begin_layout Standard
Another useful quantity is known as the oscillator strength, which measures the strength of absorption between a lower state 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ket{i}$
\end_inset

 to a high lying state 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ket{j}$
\end_inset

. This newly defined oscillator strength can be rewritten in terms of the absorption coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:fwithb}
f_{ij} = \frac{\mu}{\pi e^2}h\nu_{ji}B_{ij},
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 are the reduced mass and electronic charge of the electron respectively. In atomic units these quantities are set to unity. This allows us to obtain a relationship between the emission oscillator strength and absorption oscillator strength by substituting equation (...) into equation (..), 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f_{ij} = -\frac{g_j}{g_i}f_{ji}.
\]
\end_inset

Also from equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fwithb"

\end_inset

), the relationship between the absorption provides another useful relationship between the transition probability by applying equation (...) and equation (...), 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f_{ij} = \frac{g_j}{g_i}\frac{\mu c^3}{8\pi^2 e^2 \nu_{ji}^2}A_{ji}.
\]
\end_inset

This direct proportionality indicates that for transitions that are more likely to occur, then the strength of the line increases, as one would expect. Since the transition probability is better referred to as a rate, we must consider a time-dependent wavefunction expansion to express transitions between states. This is introduced through an external radiation field, where one such example can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\boldsymbol{A_0}\cos(\omega t - \boldsymbol{k} \cdot \boldsymbol{r})
\]
\end_inset

for an electric dipole transition. 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A_0}$
\end_inset

 is the amplitude of the radiation field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the wavenumber, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
k = ...
\]
\end_inset

To apply time-dependent perturbation theory, we can think of the radiation field as a small perturbation, and then expand the unperturbed part of the total wavefunction as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Psi = \sum_j c_j(t) \psi_j e^{-iE_jt},
\]
\end_inset

together with the corresponding absorption coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:bstrength}
B_{ij} = \frac{2}{3}\frac{c^2 \pi}{h^2 \nu_{ji}^2} \Bigg | \Braket{\psi_j | \frac{e}{\mu c}\sum_j\boldsymbol{p}_je^{i\boldsymbol{k} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}} | \psi_i} \Bigg |^2.
\end{equation}
\end_inset

The summation is carried over each electron in the system and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_j$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the momentum of electron 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

. We already have a relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}$
\end_inset

, so finding an expression for the oscillator strength is straight forward, but the difficulty arises due to the form of the exponential function. We can relax this complication by Taylor expanding the function and considering the dipole approximation, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
e^{i\boldsymbol{k} \cdot \boldsymbol{r}} = 1 + i\boldsymbol{k} \cdot \boldsymbol{r} + ... \approx 1.
\]
\end_inset

This seems like a big assumption to make, but in actual fact it is quite reasonable, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle \boldsymbol{k} \cdot \boldsymbol{r} \rangle \ll 1$
\end_inset

. The magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}$
\end_inset

 is typical of a few angstroms, compared to the magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}$
\end_inset

 defined in equation (...), which contains a 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\lambda_{ji}$
\end_inset

 term where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is typical of a few hundred to many thousand angstroms. Therefore by combining equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bstrength"

\end_inset

) and equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fwithb"

\end_inset

