\begin_layout Section
Photoionization Cross Sections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we will be focused on covering some of the basic ideology behind atomic photoionisation and its analytic process. These methods have been well establish throughout the topic of atomic physics and are adopted to the likes of here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Various atoms and ions, although we will be considering numerical investigations of positive ions only, have a multitude of energy levels. These levels are referred to as discrete states of the system. As we have seen in the discussion of the solution to the TISE (..), the energy levels can be split into fine structure terms when considering the relativistic Hamiltonian, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{BP}^{N+1}$
\end_inset

. The Hamiltonian can be split further into two -body interactions but the contributions are becoming more and more negligible that we can neglect these for the purposes of completing a calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to label each energy level through the means of some representation of the distribution of electrons in terms of the quantum numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

. Each configuration contains at least one term as to how the angular momentum of each electron is distributed amongst the subshells. The relativistic effects can split the energy levels further depending on the total spin and orbital angular momentum according to the relation (...) L-S<J<L+S. Every atom/ion has a ground state which gives rise to the lowest possible energy. In general, the energy is always taken to be 0 and every other energy level of the system is therefore relative to it (this is the ground state energy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this basic information it is now a good time to consider some atomic system denoted by A which can be present in any one of its atomic states. This atom/ion must absorb a photon of adequate energy to ionise the system to leave A in some excited state with the ejection of an electron into the continuum. The whole photoionisation process can be neatly and compactly written by the following formalism, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
h\nu+A\rightarrow A^* \rightarrow A^+ +e^-
\end{equation}
\end_inset

In order for this to occur we must assume that (following our ideology) A, at rest has some eigenenergy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_i$
\end_inset

 as an initial state with corresponding eigenstate 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_i$
\end_inset

 from (...). Likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $A^+$
\end_inset

 is left in some final state 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_f$
\end_inset

 with corresponding eigenenergy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_f$
\end_inset

. Finally, the electron emitted, otherwise known as a photoelectron, leaves the newly formed ion with some momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}_f$
\end_inset

. We approach this problem like a before (LHS of .. ) and after (RHS of ..) scenario and thus energy conservation must hold. In the adopted atomic units we can write, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
h/nu+E_i=\frac{1}{2}k_f^2+E_f
\]
\end_inset

Talk about resonances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally understanding both equations (..) and (..) gives us a proper feel of where things are going and the importance of photoionisation cross sections. since the photon energy is a direct link to the frequency, we can start to investigate various properties that arise from a range of different frequencies. This can provide multiple results which grealy advances the important research that is taking place in ares such as atomic physics and their structure. These theoretical calculations are very accurate and provide experimental agreement in order to help build the certainty in major results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now in a position to express a formula to accurately describe the photoionisation cross sections for specific transitions. It is wise to begin by defining the generalised line strength between an initial and final state i and f in the two approximations. Therefore, the dipole transition can be noted by, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_L(E_f;i)=\sum_{L,l_f}|(Ll_fE_f||D_L||i)|^2
\]
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
S_V(E_f;i)=4(E_f-E_i)^{-2}|(f||D_V||i)|^2
\]
\end_inset

as a side note, it is possible to define the oscillator strengths using simplified versions of these definitions. However, we will focus our attention to the problem at hand. The transition is between the bound state i of energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_i$
\end_inset

 to some free state f, which has a final energy of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_f=E_i+\omega$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the photon energy seen in equation (..).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The photoionisation cross sections are then defined in either length or velocity approximations by, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma_\eta=\frac{4}{3}\pi^2a_0^2\alpha\frac{\omega}{g_i}S_\eta
\end{equation}
\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=L, V$
\end_inset

 being the different formula giving rise to (..). Where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_i$
\end_inset

 is the statistical weight of the bound state and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_L\approx\sigma_V$
\end_inset

. These are generally only equal whenever exact wave functions are used which is basically an impossible task to compute. We make the best approximations possible with the computer resources available which more often than not give excellent agreement with one another.
\end_layout

